HEADWORD: Operameter
<hw>Op`er*am"e*ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>opus</ets>, <ets>operis</ets>, pl. <ets>opera</ets> work +
<ets>-meter</ets>.]</ety> <def>An instrument or machine for measuring
work done, especially for ascertaining the number of rotations made by a
machine or wheel in manufacturing cloth; a counter.</def>
<rj><au>Ure.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

